\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator of the representation indicated that the report focuses on the criteria which were flagged as reasons for non-accreditation from the initial submission. These include criteria 1\'2C 5\'2C 6 and 7.\line The evaluator indicated that the programme design is fundamentally flawed. The curriculum is based primarily on one textbook. Outcomes need to be redefined to reflect higher\'2Fappropriate levels of cognitive ability required for a qualification at this level. A clear identification and integration of learning areas\'2C together with the outcomes\'2C would achieve the stated programme goals. The stated outcomes do not reflect the level descriptors required for NQF level 6.\line Linked to the above point\'2C the evaluator felt that the scope and structure of the programme requires a thorough review. The proposed offering is still limited to fundamental project management theory. It is suggested\'2C for example\'2C that the provider considers a broader framework which links project management theory to management practice at strategic and\'2For operational levels and integration with some core\'2Frelevant management knowledge areas. In its current state\'2C it is difficult to see how the proposed programme leads to the achievement of the magnitude and level of the academic credits\'2C as contemplated. The provider does not provide any evidence of articulation possibilities with other qualifications at the same or other institutions. \line The evaluator is also of the opinion that the instructional design needs serious attention. As indicated above\'2C it is evident that the provider is seeking to design a qualification based on a textbook\'2C rather than outcomes. The categorization of one or more chapters into \'E2\'80\'9Cmodules\'E2\'80\'9D in the programme outline is also questionable as the autonomy \'28or at least semi autonomy\'29 of these \'E2\'80\'9Cmodules\'E2\'80\'9D is unclear. Finally\'2C the outline provided is actually a misrepresentation of the outline of the \'E2\'80\'9Csource\'E2\'80\'9D textbook. The prevalence of editing errors in key documents submitted for evaluation probably suggests flaws in the QA system \'E2\'80\'93 a lack of rigour and attention to critical detail. The evaluator stated that the applicant fails to demonstrate an understanding of the fundamental requirements and principles of instructional design for this qualification.\line In reviewing the representation\'2C the evaluator still feels that it remains unclear how the applicant plans to ensure that experiential learning is managed in a way which reasonably supports the achievement of the programme outcomes.  Hence while experiential learning is potentially a great vehicle for acquiring practical experience\'2C it has to be well-planned especially for a qualification at this level\'2C which requires fairly complex skills and cognitive abilities.\line Mention is made of a student website \'E2\'80\'93 but it is not clear what it would be used for and how.\line A high level description of assessment policies and procedures is provided. There is however no specific assessment strategy for this qualification. For example\'2C will the assignment\'28s\'29 be the only form of assessment\'3F Or will there be a proctored exam\'3F Evidence of all relevant assessment components\'2C their weightings and motivation of chosen strategy would paint a better picture of the appropriateness of the assessment strategy for the qualification.\line The response of the evaluator regarding Criterion 7 suggests that these concerns have largely been addressed in the representation. The evaluator noted that the evidence suggests that the minimum infrastructure required to support such a programme on distance learning is available or can easily be acquired. \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the decision not to accredit the programme be upheld mainly because of the seriousness of the flaws in the programme design. \cell \pard 

